Program No: 1
Experiment Name:
Linear Search

AIM:
To write a C program to search an element in an array using linear search.

ALGORITHM:
Linear Search Algorithm:
1.Start
2.Input the size of the array n.
3.Input the array elements A[0], A[1], ..., A[n-1].
4.Input the element to search, say key.
5.Set i = 0.
6.Repeat while i < n:
7.If A[i] = key, then print "Element found at position i" and stop.
Otherwise, increase i by 1.
8.If loop completed and element not found, print "Element not found".
9.Stop

PROGRAM:
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    int n, key, i, found = 0;
    printf("Enter the size of the array: ");
    scanf("%d", &n);

    int A[n];
    printf("Enter the %d elements: ", n);
    for(i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        scanf("%d", &A[i]);
    }

    printf("Enter the element to search: ");
    scanf("%d", &key);

    for(i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if(A[i] == key) {
            printf("Element found at position %d\n", i+1);
            found = 1;
            break;
        }
    }

    if(!found) {
        printf("Element not found\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
OUTPUT:
Enter the size of the array: 5  
Enter 5 elements: 2 10 8 12 14  
Enter the element to search: 8
The element found at position 3.

RESULT:
The program to search an element in an array using linear search was successfully implemented, executed, and the output was verified.

